STREPTOCOCCUS ZOOEPIDEMICUS, CANINE - CANADA
********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: 28 Feb 2013
Source: Fort McMurray Today.com [edited]
http://www.fortmcmurraytoday.com/2013/02/28/spca-closes-in-response-to-animal-illness-outbreak


An outbreak of strep zoo will close the doors of the Fort McMurray SPCA (Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals) until 7 Mar 2013.

The SPCA has announced a temporary closure of the shelter at the recommendation of a veterinarian due to an isolated outbreak of _Streptococcus equi sub sp. zooepidemicus_, or strep zoo, in one dog at the shelter.

The highly contagious illness is easily spread and can be passed between species, making it necessary for SPCA staff to take precautionary measures.

Strep zoo causes severe respiratory infection and can lead to hemorrhagic pneumonia, explained the SPCA release. The infection can be spread through sneezing, coughing, respiratory discharge, and can survive in the environment for up to 2 weeks if left un-sanitized.

The SPCA is recommending anyone who has visited the shelter or had an animal come in contact with an SPCA animal in the last 10 days to bear in mind the following information:

* If you notice any respiratory signs in your own animals such as sneezing, runny nose, or bloody discharge of any kind, call your vet immediately, and explain this notice to them. They may simply ask you to pick up medication instead of bringing the animal into their clinic.

* Keep any animal with clinical signs isolated from other animals.

* Minimize handling the sick animal, and change your clothes, and wash hands thoroughly.

* Do not let any human that may be ill or immune-suppressed handle the animal.

* For more information, contact your veterinarian or the SPCA at 780-743-8997.

